    <node id="1. Yes, there is a need for the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) in England to become familiar with the changes in Welsh law regarding the defense of reasonable punishment being removed. This need arises because of the potential cross-border implications and the possibility of increased awareness and scrutiny of the differences between English and Welsh law.&#10;2. The CPS in England should ensure that their staff are informed about the divergence in this area of law, as it may impact cases involving individuals from Wales being prosecuted in England or cases with cross-border elements. This can be achieved through updates to existing guidance, training programs, and internal communications.&#10;3. As the legislative process moves forward, both the CPS in Wales and England should collaborate to ensure that any changes are reflected appropriately in their guidelines, charging standards, and procedures. A coordinated approach will help maintain consistency and clarity for all parties involved in prosecutions across the border." />
