    <node id="1. The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) in Wales will conduct reviews of domestic abuse cases 18 months to 2 years after the implementation of new legislation by utilizing a system similar to their local scrutiny involvement panels. These panels involve interested parties, such as third-sector agencies representing vulnerable groups and police representatives, to discuss specific cases, including those that were previously defendable using the reasonable punishment defense but will now be referred due to the change in law.&#10;&#10;2. By bringing together relevant stakeholders, the CPS can have a frank discussion about the prosecution of these cases and use the insights gained during these reviews to shape and improve their approach to handling domestic abuse cases under the new legislation. This collaborative process will help ensure a more effective response to domestic abuse and promote culture change regarding child protection.&#10;&#10;3. The CPS may also analyze data collected on referred cases, allowing them to evaluate the impact of the new law on the number of cases being referred and prosecuted. This information can inform future evaluations and guide further adjustments to guidelines, training programs, and internal communications between the CPS in Wales and England." />
