    <node id="Yes, it is possible that the existence of a target for unsolved crimes or offenses could potentially influence the handling of criminal justice proceedings in a way that may not always be in the best interest of the child. This concern was raised during the discussion by Sian Gwenllian AM, who asked whether such targets might pressure authorities to process cases quickly and perhaps inappropriately, given the broader context of child protection.&#10;&#10;However, Barry Hughes from the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) mentioned that he didn't have much knowledge about specific targets for unsolved crimes or offenses but acknowledged that there were once targets for the police related to sanction detections. He suggested that the numbers of cases related to child protection would likely be small due to the challenges in meeting both the evidential and public interest thresholds.&#10;&#10;In summary, while there is a potential risk that performance targets could impact the handling of criminal justice proceedings in a way that may not always prioritize the best interests of the child, the specific impact would depend on the details of the targets and how they are implemented." />
    <node id=" some people going through the criminal justice system in an inappropriate way and contrary to the interests of the child, because we need to reach some target in terms of performance measures?&#10;Speaker: Barry Hughes&#10;Content: I have to say I think that extremely unlikely. In the CPS, we don't have targets for securing convictions or not. Clearly, we prosecute if we think that there's a reasonable prospect, a realistic prospect, of conviction and it's in the public interest, but we have no targets. And I would also say, because the numbers here are likely to be so small, any assertion of looking to meet targets—it's a tiny, tiny fragment of a drop in the ocean.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: What about—? There is a target for unsolved crimes, or unsolved offences. What if they fall into that category? Is that an unintended consequence?&#10;Speaker: Barry Hughes&#10;Content: I'm talking about something I don't have great knowledge of here. There was, at one stage, a series of targets for the police that bore down upon cases that secure what was called a sanction detection, which counted for Home Office figures. That disappeared some years ago. Some individual constabularies may" />
    <node id="The creation of legislation that may not result in a significant number of prosecutions still holds value as it sets clear boundaries for acceptable and unacceptable behavior. There are approximately 10,000 criminal offenses in the UK, but only about 5% of these offenses are prosecuted annually. The existence of these laws contributes to shaping societal norms and influencing behavior by sending a clear message about what is considered acceptable or not.&#10;&#10;For instance, even if there are few prosecutions related to the defense of reasonable punishment being removed, this change in law signals that certain behaviors are not tolerated and encourages culture change regarding child protection. This new legislation can influence decision-making, promote awareness about the issue at hand, and potentially lead to a reduction in such behaviors.&#10;&#10;Moreover, having laws in place can guide police investigations and encourage more reporting of these offenses, even if they are not frequently prosecuted. In summary, creating legislation like this serves a purpose in setting acceptable and unacceptable behaviors, influencing societal norms, and promoting culture change, regardless of the number of prosecutions that result from it." />
    <node id="1. Factors determining the position of a case on the spectrum: The position of a case on the spectrum of offending regarding reasonable chastisement or child abuse is determined by several factors, including the severity of the incident (such as light smacking versus repeated hitting), frequency (one-off incidents vs. repetitive behavior), the age and size of the child, the force used, and the circumstances surrounding the incident.&#10;&#10;2. Possible outcomes as the severity moves closer to the criminal threshold: As the severity of the offense moves closer to the criminal threshold, the possible outcomes include:&#10;   - Reporting to the police and taking some form of action.&#10;   - Prosecution if the case is considered serious enough, brought before a criminal court.&#10;   - Charging and dealing with it appropriately based on the specific circumstances of each case.&#10;   - In cases where there is a history of previous convictions or aggravating factors, prosecution may still be pursued even without the reasonable chastisement defense.&#10;&#10;If creating a specific flag for &quot;assault on a child - reasonable chastisement&quot; in the case management system covering England and Wales is not feasible, maintaining a manual log of every referral related to this issue can help track referred cases, allowing for analysis of how the change in law affects the number of cases being referred and prosecuted." />
    <node id="1. The difference in legal protection for adults striking children of different ages in the UK arises from the fact that there is a level of protection for an adult striking a child lightly under the present law, which is not available to the same adult for striking that child when they turn 16. This discrepancy can be attributed to the varying vulnerability and dependency levels associated with different age groups.&#10;   &#10;2. Regarding the adoption of the current approach in Wales regarding offenses against care home residents in England, there is a possibility for this to occur in the future. The legislative process to remove the defense of reasonable punishment is also happening in parallel in Scotland, and many other countries around the world have already adopted similar approaches. As the legislation moves forward, it is essential for both the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) in Wales and England to collaborate to ensure that any changes are reflected appropriately in their guidelines, charging standards, and procedures. This coordinated approach will help maintain consistency and clarity for all parties involved in prosecutions across the border." />
    <node id=" you another example. I've had considerable dealings over the years with offences against residents in care homes, and you'll have seen Winterbourne View, you'll have seen recently up in Durham, where we have adults who need to be looked after because of issues with their mental capacity, and sometimes, the carers become frustrated with them and they admonish them. Sometimes they admonish them verbally and then that turns into physical admonishment. In much the same way as children are vulnerable and are looked after and can be sometimes quite annoying—but there is a level of protection for an adult striking a child lightly under the present law that is not available to the same adult for striking that child when they turn 16. That seems to me to not necessarily fit with where we ought to be as a society.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Do you think that what we're doing in Wales will be emulated in England at some point?&#10;Speaker: Barry Hughes&#10;Content: Well, it's certainly going through in parallel in Scotland, and there are a great many other countries around the world that already have this, including a large number of European countries. Who knows? Trying to get any legislation through Westminster at the moment—who knows?" />
    <node id="1. Factors determining referral to CPS: The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) considers several factors when determining whether to prosecute a case involving light smacking, including the severity of the smack, frequency of such incidents, age and size of the child, force used, and the circumstances surrounding the incident.&#10;   &#10;2. Influence of removing the defense: If the reasonable chastisement defense is removed, it may increase the likelihood that cases of light smacking are referred to the CPS. However, this does not mean all cases will be prosecuted; the CPS would still need to consider if there is sufficient evidence and if a prosecution is in the public interest.&#10;   &#10;3. Public interest considerations: In cases where the reasonable chastisement defense no longer applies, the CPS may decide that it is not in the public interest to prosecute if the smack was light, a one-off incident, and there is no history of such behavior. However, more serious cases or those with aggravating factors might still be prosecuted even without the reasonable chastisement defense.&#10;   &#10;4. Factors affecting prosecution for repeat offenses: When applying the public interest test to a sequence of offenses, the CPS considers proportionality and takes into account various factors such as age of the offender and victim, circumstances surrounding the offense, impact on the victim, potential impact on the suspect, previous convictions, and other relevant matters listed in the code.&#10;   &#10;5. Absence of defense impact: If the reasonable chastisement defense is not available, and a sequence of three offenses occurs, the public interest test would be applied more quickly due to the repeated behavior. This distinction highlights how cases would be treated differently under the new law compared to the current situation." />
    <node id="1. Since creating a specific flag for &quot;assault on a child - reasonable chastisement&quot; in the case management system covering England and Wales is not feasible due to high costs, an alternative measure would be maintaining a manual log of every referral related to this issue. This approach allows for clear records of referred cases, enabling analysis of how the change in law affects the number of cases being referred and prosecuted. The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) should ensure that these specific details are captured and stored appropriately for future evaluation.&#10;2. A manual log might be more manageable than initially thought because the Welsh Crown Prosecution Service anticipates dealing with only a small number of cases related to reasonable chastisement, as stated by Barry Hughes.&#10;&#10;Reasons why creating a specific flag is not feasible:&#10;- High costs and difficulty in implementing such a flag on a system that covers all of England and Wales." />
    <node id="1. Increased number of cases passing the evidential stage in Wales: With the removal of the defense for reasonable punishment in Wales but not in England, there would be more cases that meet the required evidence threshold in Wales compared to England. This difference may lead to an increased number of prosecutions and convictions in Wales.&#10;2. Awareness of criminal offending: The variation in legal protections could result in confusion for individuals traveling between England and Wales, particularly those with children. An action that would be considered legal in England (e.g., lightly striking a child) might not have the same defense available in Wales, leading to potential criminal charges.&#10;3. CPS awareness and collaboration: The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) in both England and Wales will need to collaborate closely to ensure that staff are aware of the divergence in this area of law. Regular interchange of prosecutors between England and Wales requires increased communication, especially regarding aspects of Welsh law that differ from English law.&#10;4. Memorandum of Understanding (MOU): It might be helpful for both CPS in England and Wales to establish an MOU outlining their collaboration in addressing potential cross-border implications and increased awareness of legal differences. However, it is essential to prioritize updating current guidance codes to reflect the changes in Welsh law regarding the defense of reasonable punishment being removed.&#10;5. Specialized training: The CPS in Wales should consider providing specialized training for staff at the public interest stage, where more detailed knowledge will be required due to these legal differences between England and Wales." />
    <node id="Based on the information provided in the transcripts, there is a potential risk that performance targets could influence the handling of criminal justice proceedings in a way that may not always prioritize the best interests of the child. However, the specific impact would depend on the details of the targets and how they are implemented.&#10;&#10;In relation to the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS), there are no targets for securing convictions or not. The CPS prosecutes cases based on a reasonable prospect of conviction and if it's in the public interest. There is also no evidence suggesting that the CPS has any targets related to securing convictions in cases involving children.&#10;&#10;As for the police, there were once targets for what was called &quot;sanction detections,&quot; but these have since disappeared. It is unclear whether current performance measures could impact the handling of child protection cases, but the numbers involved are likely to be small, as indicated by a review in 2007 that found only 12 relevant cases over a two-year period across England and Wales.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, while there is a potential risk of children being unsuitably processed through the criminal justice system due to performance targets, the specific impact would depend on the details of the targets and how they are implemented. In the case of the CPS in Wales, there are no targets for securing convictions or not, and the numbers involved in child protection cases are likely to be small." />
    <node id="1. Yes, there could be differences in life prospects for someone convicted of a crime in Wales, as opposed to someone in England who can use the reasonable punishment defense, particularly in serious cases leading to prosecution. This is because the removal of the defense of reasonable punishment in Wales might result in an increased number of successful prosecutions and convictions compared to England. The variation in legal protections may also cause confusion for individuals traveling between the two regions, potentially leading to unintentional criminal offenses.&#10;&#10;The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) in both England and Wales will need to collaborate closely to ensure that staff are aware of the divergence in this area of law, with increased communication, specialized training, and clear records of cases being referred and prosecuted in Wales. The ultimate goal is to send a clear message about protecting children and potentially influencing societal norms and behavior, even if the chances of increased prosecutions are low." />
    <node id=" had widespread media coverage across England and Wales, and I think the Government would be well placed here to take advantage of that willingness of the media to explore something, which is potentially divisive, and I think you've probably seen some of that. Anything like that is a good story, and a good story gets out there, which means you're more likely to make people aware of it.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you. We've got some questions now on the unintended consequences from Siân Gwenllian.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Yes, we've discussed some of these already, but, for example, under the new law, or the proposed law, would one unintended consequence be that, if someone living in Wales who can't use the reasonable punishment defence—would their life prospects be different compared to those people in England, who will be able to use that defence? I think you've mentioned that in your written evidence.&#10;Speaker: Barry Hughes&#10;Content: Yes. Okay. A simple answer: if somebody in Wales is convicted—so, if it goes towards the end of the spectrum that is serious, which results in a prosecution—. It may be—" />
    <node id="The document is a transcript of a meeting between members of the Welsh Assembly discussing the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill. The participants include Lynne Neagle AM, Barry Hughes, Vikki Howells AM, Dawn Bowden AM, Suzy Davies AM, and Sian Gwenllian AM. During the meeting, they discuss various aspects of the Bill, including the age limit covered by the Children Act 2004 (which is clarified as being up to 16 years old in Wales), the public interest test, potential alternatives to prosecutions, factors affecting the Crown Prosecution Service's (CPS) decision-making process, and various barriers to implementing the proposed law.&#10;&#10;The question based on this transcript is:&#10;What are the main topics discussed during the meeting and what concerns or questions are raised by the Assembly Members regarding the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill? &#10;&#10;1. Age limit clarification: There was some confusion about the age limit covered by the Children Act 2004, with Barry Hughes stating it is up to 16, while Lynne Neagle AM mentioned it as being up to 18. The group clarifies that in Wales, it applies up to 16 years of age.&#10;2. Public interest test: Vikki Howells AM asks about the factors CPS would take into consideration when applying the public interest test regarding this Bill. Barry Hughes explains the principles and potential details of how they envision the public interest test being applied. Suzy Davies AM raises a question about seeing the draft changes to CPS guidance on the public interest test before making a final decision on supporting the Bill, but Barry Hughes believes it wouldn't be necessary.&#10;3. Potential barriers: Sian Gwenllian AM asks about how the current law protects children and discusses the concept of reasonable punishment. Barry Hughes also addresses the potential barrier posed by the shortage of registered intermediaries in Wales, mentioning that the Ministry of Justice has taken action to deal with it.&#10;&#10;Overall, Assembly Members discuss various aspects of the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill, raising concerns about age limits, public interest tests, potential alternatives, and barriers to implementing the proposed law." />
    <node id=" Thank you. Well, we've come to the end of our time. Can I thank you for attending, the three of you, and for your answers, which have been fascinating and very clear and most helpful to the committee? You will be sent a transcript following the meeting to check for accuracy. Thank you again for your time in coming here today. Diolch yn fawr.&#10;Speaker: Barry Hughes&#10;Content: Thank you. It's been a pleasure.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Item 3, then, is papers to note. Paper to note 1 is a letter from me to the Business Committee requesting an extension on the deadline for the Bill, which has now been agreed. Paper to note 2 is a letter from myself to the Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services requesting some further information from CAFCASS Cymru on the Bill. Paper to note 3 is a letter from myself to the Minister for Education regarding Diamond reform implementation ahead of our scrutiny session on 4 July. Are Members happy to note those? Item 4, then. Can I propose in accordance with Standing Order 17.42 that the committee resolves to meet in private for the remainder of the meeting? Are Members content? Thank you." />
    <node id=" who assist child witnesses during police interview and when giving evidence in court. Is this a potential barrier to implementing this proposed law, and are there any other potential barriers you want to raise?&#10;Speaker: Barry Hughes&#10;Content: No. It's a potential barrier, but I don't think it is a barrier. There was a shortage of registered intermediaries in Wales, and I know that the Ministry of Justice have taken action to deal with that, and we have had a number of people who are now in a position to act as intermediaries. Now, of course, if they were to decide not to do that anymore, we may have a problem, but, in turn, we would be looking to recruit more people into those positions. So, yes, it has the potential to serve as a barrier, but in practice, I don't think it would be a barrier. I think, particularly given the very low numbers we're talking about, we would be able to manage it. I've got no significant concerns, I have to say.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Thank you. Well, we've come to the end of our time. Can I thank you for attending, the three of you, and for your answers," />
