    <edge source="1. The current state of the law regarding reasonable punishment as a defense for children in Wales is that it is governed by section 58 of the Children Act 2004, which provides a legal defense for a person accused of assaulting a child if they can prove that it was reasonable chastisement.&#10;2. The witnesses present to provide their views on the related bill are Barry Hughes (Chief Crown Prosecutor for Wales), Kwame Biney (senior policy advisor, CPS), and Iwan Jenkins (head of the complex casework unit, Crown Prosecution Service Cymru Wales)." target="1. Factors determining referral to CPS: The factors that determine whether a case of light smacking would be referred to the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) include the severity of the smack, the frequency of such incidents, the age and size of the child, the force used, and the circumstances surrounding the incident.&#10;2. Influence of removing the defense: If the reasonable chastisement defense is removed, it would likely increase the possibility that cases of light smacking are referred to the CPS. However, this does not necessarily mean that all cases will be prosecuted. The CPS would still need to consider whether there is sufficient evidence and if a prosecution is in the public interest.&#10;3. Public interest considerations: In cases where the reasonable chastisement defense no longer applies, the CPS may decide that it is not in the public interest to prosecute if the smack was light, a one-off incident, and there is no history of such behavior. However, more serious cases or those with aggravating factors might still be prosecuted even without the reasonable chastisement defense.">
