    <edge source="1. The current state of the law regarding reasonable punishment as a defense for children in Wales is that it is governed by section 58 of the Children Act 2004, which provides a legal defense for a person accused of assaulting a child if they can prove that it was reasonable chastisement.&#10;2. The witnesses present to provide their views on the related bill are Barry Hughes (Chief Crown Prosecutor for Wales), Kwame Biney (senior policy advisor, CPS), and Iwan Jenkins (head of the complex casework unit, Crown Prosecution Service Cymru Wales)." target="1. The difference in legal protection for adults striking children of different ages in the UK arises from the fact that there is a level of protection for an adult striking a child lightly under the present law, which is not available to the same adult for striking that child when they turn 16. This discrepancy can be attributed to the varying vulnerability and dependency levels associated with different age groups.&#10;   &#10;2. Regarding the adoption of the current approach in Wales regarding offenses against care home residents in England, there is a possibility for this to occur in the future. The legislative process to remove the defense of reasonable punishment is also happening in parallel in Scotland, and many other countries around the world have already adopted similar approaches. As the legislation moves forward, it is essential for both the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) in Wales and England to collaborate to ensure that any changes are reflected appropriately in their guidelines, charging standards, and procedures. This coordinated approach will help maintain consistency and clarity for all parties involved in prosecutions across the border.">
