    <edge source=": Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Thank you very much. I would like to start just by looking in general at how the law currently stands, and how do you think the law as it currently stands today, and specifically in terms of reasonable punishment—how does that protect children.&#10;Speaker: Barry Hughes&#10;Content: Sorry, can I just be clear? How does the law as it presently stands protect children?&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Yes.&#10;Speaker: Barry Hughes&#10;Content: We have a range of offences created by the criminal law, going back to the Offences Against the Person Act 1861 in the middle of the century before last, which provide for offences of assault against a variety of people, including, in particular, Acts such as the Children and Young Persons Act 1933, which provides for offences that are specific to children. But the more general criminal legislation, such as the Offences Against the Person Act, does provide specifically for adults and children alike not to be subject to physical assault. In respect of children in particular, you'll be aware that we have section 58 of the Children Act 2004, which does make it a defence for a person accused of assaulting a child to argue that it" target="The document is a transcript of a meeting between members of the Welsh Assembly discussing the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill. The participants include Lynne Neagle AM, Barry Hughes, Vikki Howells AM, Dawn Bowden AM, Suzy Davies AM, and Sian Gwenllian AM. During the meeting, they discuss various aspects of the Bill, including the age limit covered by the Children Act 2004 (which is clarified as being up to 16 years old in Wales), the public interest test, potential alternatives to prosecutions, factors affecting the Crown Prosecution Service's (CPS) decision-making process, and various barriers to implementing the proposed law.&#10;&#10;The question based on this transcript is:&#10;What are the main topics discussed during the meeting and what concerns or questions are raised by the Assembly Members regarding the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill? &#10;&#10;1. Age limit clarification: There was some confusion about the age limit covered by the Children Act 2004, with Barry Hughes stating it is up to 16, while Lynne Neagle AM mentioned it as being up to 18. The group clarifies that in Wales, it applies up to 16 years of age.&#10;2. Public interest test: Vikki Howells AM asks about the factors CPS would take into consideration when applying the public interest test regarding this Bill. Barry Hughes explains the principles and potential details of how they envision the public interest test being applied. Suzy Davies AM raises a question about seeing the draft changes to CPS guidance on the public interest test before making a final decision on supporting the Bill, but Barry Hughes believes it wouldn't be necessary.&#10;3. Potential barriers: Sian Gwenllian AM asks about how the current law protects children and discusses the concept of reasonable punishment. Barry Hughes also addresses the potential barrier posed by the shortage of registered intermediaries in Wales, mentioning that the Ministry of Justice has taken action to deal with it.&#10;&#10;Overall, Assembly Members discuss various aspects of the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill, raising concerns about age limits, public interest tests, potential alternatives, and barriers to implementing the proposed law.">
