    <edge source=".&#10;Speaker: Barry Hughes&#10;Content: In addition to those that I've mentioned, probably not. It boils down to the fact that there's a defence in England for assaults upon children that isn't available in Wales if this Bill goes through, and then it's dealing with the consequences of that.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: Okay. That's fine. Thank you, Chair.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: I've got a supplementary from Suzy, and then Siân.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Thank you. I was going to ask this question later, but I think it fits in—. I've forgotten what I was going to ask; this is terrible. Oh no, that's right—obviously, this Act is on a particular trajectory at the moment, and it's due to be introduced before the end of this Assembly. Do you think it would be better for us as scrutinisers of this Act if we could see the draft changes to CPS guidance on the public interest test before we make our final decision?&#10;Speaker: Barry Hughes&#10;Content: I honestly don't think that would necessarily be helpful. I've had some discussions with" target="The document is a transcript of a meeting between members of the Welsh Assembly discussing the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill. The participants include Lynne Neagle AM, Barry Hughes, Vikki Howells AM, Dawn Bowden AM, Suzy Davies AM, and Sian Gwenllian AM. During the meeting, they discuss various aspects of the Bill, including the age limit covered by the Children Act 2004 (which is clarified as being up to 16 years old in Wales), the public interest test, potential alternatives to prosecutions, factors affecting the Crown Prosecution Service's (CPS) decision-making process, and various barriers to implementing the proposed law.&#10;&#10;The question based on this transcript is:&#10;What are the main topics discussed during the meeting and what concerns or questions are raised by the Assembly Members regarding the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill? &#10;&#10;1. Age limit clarification: There was some confusion about the age limit covered by the Children Act 2004, with Barry Hughes stating it is up to 16, while Lynne Neagle AM mentioned it as being up to 18. The group clarifies that in Wales, it applies up to 16 years of age.&#10;2. Public interest test: Vikki Howells AM asks about the factors CPS would take into consideration when applying the public interest test regarding this Bill. Barry Hughes explains the principles and potential details of how they envision the public interest test being applied. Suzy Davies AM raises a question about seeing the draft changes to CPS guidance on the public interest test before making a final decision on supporting the Bill, but Barry Hughes believes it wouldn't be necessary.&#10;3. Potential barriers: Sian Gwenllian AM asks about how the current law protects children and discusses the concept of reasonable punishment. Barry Hughes also addresses the potential barrier posed by the shortage of registered intermediaries in Wales, mentioning that the Ministry of Justice has taken action to deal with it.&#10;&#10;Overall, Assembly Members discuss various aspects of the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill, raising concerns about age limits, public interest tests, potential alternatives, and barriers to implementing the proposed law.">
