    <edge source="1. When applying the public interest test in determining whether or not to prosecute a person for a sequence of three offences, several factors are considered, including the age of the offender and victim, the circumstances surrounding the offense, the impact on the victim, and the likelihood of recurrence.&#10;2. If there is a history of previous convictions, it is more likely that prosecution will be pursued. However, the law does not guarantee that prosecution will always follow.&#10;3. In the current situation, where a defense such as reasonable chastisement may be applicable, it may prevent prosecution if the defense is satisfied. However, if this defense did not apply at all and there were a sequence of three offenses, the public interest test would come to the fore more quickly due to repeated behavior.&#10;4. The distinction between the current situation and how things would be in the future lies in the availability of the defense. If the defense is not available, the public interest test becomes more significant, and a proportionate approach will be taken based on the specific circumstances of each case." target=" the defence stops applying. If that defence didn't apply at all, and we had a sequence of three offences, the public interest test would kick in, if I may put it like that, pretty quickly, because it would be repeated behaviour. So, that would be the distinction between how things are now and how they would be in the future, because the defence would not be available, so the public interest test would then come to the fore that much more quickly. So, when we apply the public interest test, the essence of it is about proportionality, and trying to come up with an approach that is proportionate to the offending. We look at the age of the offender, the age of the victim, we look at the circumstances, we look at the impact upon the victim, we look at the impact that's likely in relation to the suspect, and there is, within the code, 