    <edge source="1. When applying the public interest test in determining whether or not to prosecute a person for a sequence of three offences, several factors are considered, including the age of the offender and victim, the circumstances surrounding the offense, the impact on the victim, and the likelihood of recurrence.&#10;2. If there is a history of previous convictions, it is more likely that prosecution will be pursued. However, the law does not guarantee that prosecution will always follow.&#10;3. In the current situation, where a defense such as reasonable chastisement may be applicable, it may prevent prosecution if the defense is satisfied. However, if this defense did not apply at all and there were a sequence of three offenses, the public interest test would come to the fore more quickly due to repeated behavior.&#10;4. The distinction between the current situation and how things would be in the future lies in the availability of the defense. If the defense is not available, the public interest test becomes more significant, and a proportionate approach will be taken based on the specific circumstances of each case." target="1. Factors determining the position of a case on the spectrum: The position of a case on the spectrum of offending regarding reasonable chastisement or child abuse is determined by several factors, including the severity of the incident (such as light smacking versus repeated hitting), frequency (one-off incidents vs. repetitive behavior), the age and size of the child, the force used, and the circumstances surrounding the incident.&#10;&#10;2. Possible outcomes as the severity moves closer to the criminal threshold: As the severity of the offense moves closer to the criminal threshold, the possible outcomes include:&#10;   - Reporting to the police and taking some form of action.&#10;   - Prosecution if the case is considered serious enough, brought before a criminal court.&#10;   - Charging and dealing with it appropriately based on the specific circumstances of each case.&#10;   - In cases where there is a history of previous convictions or aggravating factors, prosecution may still be pursued even without the reasonable chastisement defense.&#10;&#10;If creating a specific flag for &quot;assault on a child - reasonable chastisement&quot; in the case management system covering England and Wales is not feasible, maintaining a manual log of every referral related to this issue can help track referred cases, allowing for analysis of how the change in law affects the number of cases being referred and prosecuted.">
