rosecute if the smack was light, a one-off incident, and there is no history of such behavior. However, more serious cases or those with aggravating factors might still be prosecuted even without the reasonable chastisement defense.&#10;   &#10;4. Factors affecting prosecution for repeat offenses: When applying the public interest test to a sequence of offenses, the CPS considers proportionality and takes into account various factors such as age of the offender and victim, circumstances surrounding the offense, impact on the victim, potential impact on the suspect, previous convictions, and other relevant matters listed in the code.&#10;   &#10;5. Absence of defense impact: If the reasonable chastisement defense is not available, and a sequence of three offenses occurs, the public interest test would be applied more quickly due to the repeated behavior. This distinction highlights how cases would be treated differently under the new law compared to the current situation.">
