provided an example illustrating how things might change under the new law:&#10;&#10;* A case where a parent gives their child multiple smacks (two or three) could potentially meet the evidential threshold for prosecution, as the defense would not be available.&#10;* However, the CPS may determine that pursuing prosecution is not in the public interest because it was an isolated incident without any history of abuse, and the level of harm inflicted was minimal. In this case, the CPS might decide not to prosecute.&#10;&#10;The CPS would need to create more detailed guidance for prosecutors on how to apply these factors specifically in relation to the Bill. However, Barry Hughes noted that providing too much detail upfront could be counterproductive and advocated for a more gradual approach in developing such guidelines.">
