    <edge source=" of the potential divergence of Welsh law. We will issue policy guidance and charging standards to reflect any changes as they arise. And we think that we are sufficiently flexible to take account of that.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: Okay. So, would you see the necessity for a memorandum of understanding, for instance, or it being useful in these circumstances, or are you quite satisfied that the current guidance code would cover that?&#10;Speaker: Barry Hughes&#10;Content: Well, it's yet to move from a Bill into an Act, so we'd need to make sure that happened. We know there would be a period of time, perhaps as much as two years, or maybe a little more, while that takes place. There will be a further series of awareness raising. We have strategic implementation groups—Iwan sits on that group. So, we would build ourselves up to come up with the appropriate guidance according to the circumstances. In terms of how we'd approach it within the Crown Prosecution Service in Cymru-Wales, my approach would be along the lines of working with Kwame and his colleagues to make sure that the guidance that we issue nationally suits both England and Wales. And when it comes to the practical application of the legislation" target="1. The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) in England will need to familiarize themselves with the changes in Welsh law regarding the defense of reasonable punishment being removed due to potential cross-border implications and increased awareness and scrutiny of differences between English and Welsh law.&#10;2. To ensure that CPS staff are informed about this divergence, they should update existing guidance, provide training programs, and use internal communications to share information about the changes in Welsh law.&#10;3. As the legislative process moves forward, both the CPS in Wales and England should collaborate to reflect any changes appropriately in their guidelines, charging standards, and procedures, maintaining consistency and clarity for prosecutions across the border.&#10;4. The CPS in Wales will work with their counterparts in England to ensure that guidance issued nationally is suitable for both jurisdictions. In Wales, a small number of specialists will be trained to handle cases related to this new legislation, fostering a close network of experts.&#10;5. The Crown Prosecution Service should consider engaging in awareness-raising efforts to help the Act achieve its intended goals once it has been passed.">
