    <edge source="The question raised by Suzy Davies AM is about whether it would be more effective to create new civil law to promote culture change regarding child protection, rather than focusing on changing the existing criminal legislation.&#10;&#10;Barry Hughes' response suggests that even though the chances of increased prosecutions might be low, the value of the proposed legislation lies in sending a clear message that there is a greater degree of protection for children. He compares this approach to the evolution of law seen in many other countries around the world. By removing the defense of reasonable punishment, the public interest test becomes more significant, and a proportionate approach will be taken based on the specific circumstances of each case.&#10;&#10;In summary, the focus is on changing the law instead of creating new civil law because, even with low chances of increased prosecutions, the value comes from sending a clear message about protecting children and potentially influencing societal norms and behavior." target="Yes, it is possible that the existence of a target for unsolved crimes or offenses could potentially influence the handling of criminal justice proceedings in a way that may not always be in the best interest of the child. This concern was raised during the discussion by Sian Gwenllian AM, who asked whether such targets might pressure authorities to process cases quickly and perhaps inappropriately, given the broader context of child protection.&#10;&#10;However, Barry Hughes from the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) mentioned that he didn't have much knowledge about specific targets for unsolved crimes or offenses but acknowledged that there were once targets for the police related to sanction detections. He suggested that the numbers of cases related to child protection would likely be small due to the challenges in meeting both the evidential and public interest thresholds.&#10;&#10;In summary, while there is a potential risk that performance targets could impact the handling of criminal justice proceedings in a way that may not always prioritize the best interests of the child, the specific impact would depend on the details of the targets and how they are implemented.">
