    <edge source="The question raised by Suzy Davies AM is about whether it would be more effective to create new civil law to promote culture change regarding child protection, rather than focusing on changing the existing criminal legislation.&#10;&#10;Barry Hughes' response suggests that even though the chances of increased prosecutions might be low, the value of the proposed legislation lies in sending a clear message that there is a greater degree of protection for children. He compares this approach to the evolution of law seen in many other countries around the world. By removing the defense of reasonable punishment, the public interest test becomes more significant, and a proportionate approach will be taken based on the specific circumstances of each case.&#10;&#10;In summary, the focus is on changing the law instead of creating new civil law because, even with low chances of increased prosecutions, the value comes from sending a clear message about protecting children and potentially influencing societal norms and behavior." target="1. Factors determining the position of a case on the spectrum: The position of a case on the spectrum of offending regarding reasonable chastisement or child abuse is determined by several factors, including the severity of the incident (such as light smacking versus repeated hitting), frequency (one-off incidents vs. repetitive behavior), the age and size of the child, the force used, and the circumstances surrounding the incident.&#10;&#10;2. Possible outcomes as the severity moves closer to the criminal threshold: As the severity of the offense moves closer to the criminal threshold, the possible outcomes include:&#10;   - Reporting to the police and taking some form of action.&#10;   - Prosecution if the case is considered serious enough, brought before a criminal court.&#10;   - Charging and dealing with it appropriately based on the specific circumstances of each case.&#10;   - In cases where there is a history of previous convictions or aggravating factors, prosecution may still be pursued even without the reasonable chastisement defense.&#10;&#10;If creating a specific flag for &quot;assault on a child - reasonable chastisement&quot; in the case management system covering England and Wales is not feasible, maintaining a manual log of every referral related to this issue can help track referred cases, allowing for analysis of how the change in law affects the number of cases being referred and prosecuted.">
