    <edge source="The question raised by Suzy Davies AM is about whether it would be more effective to create new civil law to promote culture change regarding child protection, rather than focusing on changing the existing criminal legislation.&#10;&#10;Barry Hughes' response suggests that even though the chances of increased prosecutions might be low, the value of the proposed legislation lies in sending a clear message that there is a greater degree of protection for children. He compares this approach to the evolution of law seen in many other countries around the world. By removing the defense of reasonable punishment, the public interest test becomes more significant, and a proportionate approach will be taken based on the specific circumstances of each case.&#10;&#10;In summary, the focus is on changing the law instead of creating new civil law because, even with low chances of increased prosecutions, the value comes from sending a clear message about protecting children and potentially influencing societal norms and behavior." target="Based on the information provided in the transcripts, there is a potential risk that performance targets could influence the handling of criminal justice proceedings in a way that may not always prioritize the best interests of the child. However, the specific impact would depend on the details of the targets and how they are implemented.&#10;&#10;In relation to the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS), there are no targets for securing convictions or not. The CPS prosecutes cases based on a reasonable prospect of conviction and if it's in the public interest. There is also no evidence suggesting that the CPS has any targets related to securing convictions in cases involving children.&#10;&#10;As for the police, there were once targets for what was called &quot;sanction detections,&quot; but these have since disappeared. It is unclear whether current performance measures could impact the handling of child protection cases, but the numbers involved are likely to be small, as indicated by a review in 2007 that found only 12 relevant cases over a two-year period across England and Wales.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, while there is a potential risk of children being unsuitably processed through the criminal justice system due to performance targets, the specific impact would depend on the details of the targets and how they are implemented. In the case of the CPS in Wales, there are no targets for securing convictions or not, and the numbers involved in child protection cases are likely to be small.">
