    <edge source="The question raised by Suzy Davies AM is about whether it would be more effective to create new civil law to promote culture change regarding child protection, rather than focusing on changing the existing criminal legislation.&#10;&#10;Barry Hughes' response suggests that even though the chances of increased prosecutions might be low, the value of the proposed legislation lies in sending a clear message that there is a greater degree of protection for children. He compares this approach to the evolution of law seen in many other countries around the world. By removing the defense of reasonable punishment, the public interest test becomes more significant, and a proportionate approach will be taken based on the specific circumstances of each case.&#10;&#10;In summary, the focus is on changing the law instead of creating new civil law because, even with low chances of increased prosecutions, the value comes from sending a clear message about protecting children and potentially influencing societal norms and behavior." target="1. Yes, there could be differences in life prospects for someone convicted of a crime in Wales, as opposed to someone in England who can use the reasonable punishment defense, particularly in serious cases leading to prosecution. This is because the removal of the defense of reasonable punishment in Wales might result in an increased number of successful prosecutions and convictions compared to England. The variation in legal protections may also cause confusion for individuals traveling between the two regions, potentially leading to unintentional criminal offenses.&#10;&#10;The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) in both England and Wales will need to collaborate closely to ensure that staff are aware of the divergence in this area of law, with increased communication, specialized training, and clear records of cases being referred and prosecuted in Wales. The ultimate goal is to send a clear message about protecting children and potentially influencing societal norms and behavior, even if the chances of increased prosecutions are low.">
