    <edge source="1. In order to assess the impact of the new law, the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) in Wales will need to maintain clear records of any cases that are referred to them from the police, specifically noting details of cases that were previously defendable using the reasonable punishment defense but will now be referred due to the change in law. This data collection will allow for analysis of how the change in law is impacting the number of cases being referred and prosecuted. The CPS already keeps records of cases, but with this change, they will need to ensure that these specific details relevant to the new law are captured and stored appropriately for future evaluation.&#10;&#10;2. While there are no significant financial consequences expected for the CPS as a result of the new law, some minor additional resources may be required to facilitate the necessary changes in guidelines, training programs, and internal communications between the CPS in Wales and England. This collaboration will ensure consistency and clarity for prosecutions across the border.&#10;&#10;3. The CPS does not have the power to direct the police, but by maintaining a clear record of cases and their outcomes, they can help promote culture change regarding child protection and potentially influence societal norms and behavior. Removing the defense of reasonable punishment increases the significance of the public interest test and ensures a proportionate approach based on the specific circumstances of each case." target="1. The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) in Wales will conduct reviews of domestic abuse cases 18 months to 2 years after the implementation of new legislation by utilizing a system similar to their local scrutiny involvement panels. These panels involve interested parties, such as third-sector agencies representing vulnerable groups and police representatives, to discuss specific cases, including those that were previously defendable using the reasonable punishment defense but will now be referred due to the change in law.&#10;&#10;2. By bringing together relevant stakeholders, the CPS can have a frank discussion about the prosecution of these cases and use the insights gained during these reviews to shape and improve their approach to handling domestic abuse cases under the new legislation. This collaborative process will help ensure a more effective response to domestic abuse and promote culture change regarding child protection.&#10;&#10;3. The CPS may also analyze data collected on referred cases, allowing them to evaluate the impact of the new law on the number of cases being referred and prosecuted. This information can inform future evaluations and guide further adjustments to guidelines, training programs, and internal communications between the CPS in Wales and England.">
