sion about the prosecution of these cases and help shape and improve the CPS's approach to handling upskirting offences under the new legislation.&#10;3. The CPS can also analyze data collected on referred upskirting cases, allowing them to evaluate the impact of the new law on the number of cases being referred and prosecuted. This information can inform future evaluations and guide further adjustments to guidelines, training programs, and internal communications between the CPS in Wales and England.&#10;4. Collaboration with lawmakers and other relevant stakeholders will ensure that any changes in Welsh law are accurately reflected in CPS guidelines, charging standards, and procedures, helping maintain consistency and clarity for all parties involved in prosecutions across the border.">
