    <edge source="1. The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) in Wales will conduct reviews of domestic abuse cases 18 months to 2 years after the implementation of new legislation by utilizing a system similar to their local scrutiny involvement panels. These panels involve interested parties, such as third-sector agencies representing vulnerable groups and police representatives, to discuss specific cases, including those that were previously defendable using the reasonable punishment defense but will now be referred due to the change in law.&#10;&#10;2. By bringing together relevant stakeholders, the CPS can have a frank discussion about the prosecution of these cases and use the insights gained during these reviews to shape and improve their approach to handling domestic abuse cases under the new legislation. This collaborative process will help ensure a more effective response to domestic abuse and promote culture change regarding child protection.&#10;&#10;3. The CPS may also analyze data collected on referred cases, allowing them to evaluate the impact of the new law on the number of cases being referred and prosecuted. This information can inform future evaluations and guide further adjustments to guidelines, training programs, and internal communications between the CPS in Wales and England." target="Based on the information provided in the transcripts, there is a potential risk that performance targets could influence the handling of criminal justice proceedings in a way that may not always prioritize the best interests of the child. However, the specific impact would depend on the details of the targets and how they are implemented.&#10;&#10;In relation to the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS), there are no targets for securing convictions or not. The CPS prosecutes cases based on a reasonable prospect of conviction and if it's in the public interest. There is also no evidence suggesting that the CPS has any targets related to securing convictions in cases involving children.&#10;&#10;As for the police, there were once targets for what was called &quot;sanction detections,&quot; but these have since disappeared. It is unclear whether current performance measures could impact the handling of child protection cases, but the numbers involved are likely to be small, as indicated by a review in 2007 that found only 12 relevant cases over a two-year period across England and Wales.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, while there is a potential risk of children being unsuitably processed through the criminal justice system due to performance targets, the specific impact would depend on the details of the targets and how they are implemented. In the case of the CPS in Wales, there are no targets for securing convictions or not, and the numbers involved in child protection cases are likely to be small.">
