    <edge source="The document is a transcript of a meeting between members of the Welsh Assembly discussing the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill. The participants include Lynne Neagle AM, Barry Hughes, Vikki Howells AM, Dawn Bowden AM, Suzy Davies AM, and Sian Gwenllian AM. During the meeting, they discuss various aspects of the Bill, including the age limit covered by the Children Act 2004 (which is clarified as being up to 16 years old in Wales), the public interest test, potential alternatives to prosecutions, factors affecting the Crown Prosecution Service's (CPS) decision-making process, and various barriers to implementing the proposed law.&#10;&#10;The question based on this transcript is:&#10;What are the main topics discussed during the meeting and what concerns or questions are raised by the Assembly Members regarding the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill? &#10;&#10;1. Age limit clarification: There was some confusion about the age limit covered by the Children Act 2004, with Barry Hughes stating it is up to 16, while Lynne Neagle AM mentioned it as being up to 18. The group clarifies that in Wales, it applies up to 16 years of age.&#10;2. Public interest test: Vikki Howells AM asks about the factors CPS would take into consideration when applying the public interest test regarding this Bill. Barry Hughes explains the principles and potential details of how they envision the public interest test being applied. Suzy Davies AM raises a question about seeing the draft changes to CPS guidance on the public interest test before making a final decision on supporting the Bill, but Barry Hughes believes it wouldn't be necessary.&#10;3. Potential barriers: Sian Gwenllian AM asks about how the current law protects children and discusses the concept of reasonable punishment. Barry Hughes also addresses the potential barrier posed by the shortage of registered intermediaries in Wales, mentioning that the Ministry of Justice has taken action to deal with it.&#10;&#10;Overall, Assembly Members discuss various aspects of the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill, raising concerns about age limits, public interest tests, potential alternatives, and barriers to implementing the proposed law." target=" Thank you. Well, we've come to the end of our time. Can I thank you for attending, the three of you, and for your answers, which have been fascinating and very clear and most helpful to the committee? You will be sent a transcript following the meeting to check for accuracy. Thank you again for your time in coming here today. Diolch yn fawr.&#10;Speaker: Barry Hughes&#10;Content: Thank you. It's been a pleasure.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Item 3, then, is papers to note. Paper to note 1 is a letter from me to the Business Committee requesting an extension on the deadline for the Bill, which has now been agreed. Paper to note 2 is a letter from myself to the Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services requesting some further information from CAFCASS Cymru on the Bill. Paper to note 3 is a letter from myself to the Minister for Education regarding Diamond reform implementation ahead of our scrutiny session on 4 July. Are Members happy to note those? Item 4, then. Can I propose in accordance with Standing Order 17.42 that the committee resolves to meet in private for the remainder of the meeting? Are Members content? Thank you.">
